    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>3. Tulli historia regia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tullus Hostilius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>3. The royal history of Tullus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Tullus, alter Romulus: eoq[ue] aptior Romano regno, ad maiora aspiranti.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tullus Hostilius"/>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tullus is another Romulus, and therefore highly suited for a Roman rule that aims very high.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Principatus viros declarat. Vt circa id tempus Pittacus, vnus sapientum vt etiam s[upr]a, i[nfr]a.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Pittacus of Mytilene"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The principate reveals men. Such as Pittacus around this time, one of the wise men, like also above and below.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Prudens, et fortis Albani Oratio: ad regem Tullu[m]. Mixt&egrave; etiam temperans, et iusta. Vt Livij potius, qua[m] Albani videatur oratio. Aut salte[m] Romano stylo limata: vt multae Barbaroru[m] conciones i[infr]a. 
                        Sufficiat, semel initio observasse. Liuius semper est Liuius: quicunq[ue] erant Oratores. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tullus Hostilius"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Albanus’ intelligent and strong speech to king Tullus, in a varied way both restrained and correct, so that it rather seems to be Livy's speech than that of Albanus. Or at least it is polished in the Roman style, 
                like in many speeches of the Barbarians below. It may suffice to pay attention once in the beginning. Livy always remains Livy, whoever the orators were.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Foederum ratio.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The principle of treaties.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian"  anchor_text="foecialis">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>f[o]ecialis.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>the fetial priest.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>s[upr]a, in regno Anci.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>See above in Ancus’s reign.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian"  anchor_text="pater patratus">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>paterpatratus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="paterpatratus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The felitial's spokesman.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>King at arms, or king
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        of heralds. Now no preist, but an officer of court, quali fide for that royall seruice.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Ius feciale: &agrave; Sigonio non satis expressum; &agrave; Bodino pleni&ugrave;s tractatum, et rei gerenda[e] efficacius, libro 5. de Republica. Vbi de foederibus, politic&egrave;, et pragmatic&egrave;. Legatis Tractatus singularis.
                        Feciales dicti, &agrave; faciendo, qu&ograve;d belli, pacisq[ue] facienda[e] apud eos ius esset. Festus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Carlo Sigonio"/>
                    <person name="Jean Bodin"/>
                    <person name="Sextus Pompeius Festus"/>
                    <book title="De verborum significatu"/>
                    <book title="De Republica"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Herald Lawe, or Legate Lawe.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The fetial law: Sigonius does not adequately describe this; Bodin discusses it in more detail and treats its task more effectively in his De republica, book 5, where he writes about treaties from a 
                political and pragmatic perspective - a remarkable treatise for diplomats. The ‘fetial’ priests are called that way from ‘faciendus’, since it was their authority to make war or peace. Festus.
                Herald Lawe, or Legate Lawe.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
